                        <p style="margin: 0 0 0.2em;font-size: 110%;color: #454242 !important;font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><a href="http://org2.salsalabs.com/dia/track.jsp?v=2&c=YElgeSjx%2BYGbUaf%2F8kB6f6dsVJBHu7q7" style="text-decoration: none; color: #570000"><strong>If a Senator Can't Report Sexual Harassment Without Backlash, Who Can?</strong></a></p>
                        <p style="margin: 0;padding: 0;font-size: 100%;color: #444 !important;font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;line-height: 1.1"><strong>Crystal Shepeard, Care2:</strong>&#160;Women have to walk a tricky tightrope of not wanting to seem too "sensitive," while at the same time standing up for themselves in the face of discrimination. Sen. Gillibrand's experience shows how difficult it can be for anyone to navigate the workplace without inviting negative consequences.</p>
